And thanks for your detailed response. You are obviously not a slave 
to convention.

It confirms one thing: people who actively use Quickscript, have 
every need/right to change it and nuance it, since shorthand is first 
and foremost an intrapersonal means of communication.

I understand that even the professionals (court reporters) who use a 
suuposedly &quot;common system&quot; cannot 100% translate each other&#39;s work. 
I even heard that one trial was dismissed because the reporter died 
before he could translate his notes - there was no legal record of 
the event possible!

Along the line of your &quot;lightning&quot; comments - (and to show you that 
we basically agree) I have had a peeve for a long time about the 
writing of &quot;pity&quot; in Ancrocles.  There it is piti. Which makes no 
sense to me at all. Try saying &quot;pity&quot; making the 2 vowels identical! 
You feel like a comic butler in an Agatha Christie mystery. And just 
about as natural. 



